Linux:
  create an alias (a custom command) using the 'alias' command as root.
  eg: I need a command to head to the web root directory:
    use: alias wr = "cd /var/www/html"
    when I type wr; the directory will be headed there
    ***This is a temporary alias.*** -- the command will be stored for the current terminal only.
    
    <h>Permanent Alias</h>
    To create a permament alias; edit the ~/.bashrc or ~/.bash_aliases file using vim or nano
    edit as:
      alias = <command>
      (save with :w in vim)
    
    quick command:
    echo alias <custom_alias> = <command> >> ~/.bash_aliases
    
